Professor of Biostatistics and Data Science at Brown

34
00:01:56.660 --> 00:01:58.380
University. Welcome.

35
00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:11.700
Thank you.

36
00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:17.440
Thank you all for coming out this afternoon to talk with us a bit about methods for

37
00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:21.120
incorporating real world data into clinical trial design.

38
00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:25.680
So I'm a biostatistician, and what I'm going to emphasize in my talk

39
00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:29.720
is both design and analysis issues in incorporating

40
00:02:29.780 --> 00:02:33.660
real world data into clinical trials, but particularly thinking about the

41
00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:37.660
unique aspects of real world data and how that might inform the

42
00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:41.710
way that we think about combining them with trial data in a way that

43
00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:45.680
allows us to learn more and address the deficiencies of trials

44
00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:48.840
without degrading the quality of the evidence that we're generating.

45
00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:56.660
We are currently in an era of enormous enthusiasm

46
00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:00.580
for incorporating real world data into research broadly,

47
00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:04.820
and I think that's been particularly spurred by the

48
00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:08.820
uptick in use of AI and AI allowing us to

49
00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:12.560
access data and unleash data from electronic health records, for

50
00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:16.220
instance, that's in narrative text form that we haven't previously been able to

51
00:03:16.240 --> 00:03:19.820
access. So this is an example of three articles from

52
00:03:19.900 --> 00:03:23.880
recent lay press publications. These came out spanning

53
00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:25.440
the period from October,

54
00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:30.280
no, August of 2025, up through December of 2025, and I

55
00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:33.490
found those within a few seconds of just Google searching for real world data and

56
00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:37.490
health. So there's a ton of enthusiasm about conducting this

57
00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:41.360
kind of research and a lot of hype and promise

58
00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:44.140
and potential for doing this work.

59
00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:47.860
But I think we need to ground all of our analyses and all of our thinking

60
00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:51.920
about the work in a realization that the data are messy,

61
00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:55.640
they are challenging, and it's going to take a lot of methodological

62
00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:59.640
innovation and careful attention to analytic details if we're going to

63
00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:03.260
realize the kind of potential and the kind of promise

64
00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:05.520
that these sort of headlines are touting.

65
00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:13.500
Why is there such enthusiasm for potentially doing this, for

66
00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:17.041
incorporating real world data into randomized control trial design?

67
00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:21.440
We know that clinical trials, randomized trials, are considered the gold

68
00:04:21.541 --> 00:04:24.760
standard for generating estimates of treatment efficacy.

69
00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:29.110
So we already have a design approach that people

70
00:04:29.140 --> 00:04:32.820
feel confident in and that we know reduces risks of certain types of

71
00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:33.380
bias.

72
00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:37.860
But we also know that clinical trials have numerous deficiencies,

73
00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:42.040
most notably that they are extremely expensive, they're

74
00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:46.120
slow, many trials fail to meet their enrollment targets, and there

75
00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:49.870
are just many, many comparisons of different treatment combinations,

76
00:04:50.180 --> 00:04:53.550
different treatment regimens and patterns that we might be interested in, and it's

77
00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:57.350
simply infeasible to conduct a randomized control trial for every single one of

78
00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:00.940
them. So bringing into our research

79
00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:04.440
portfolio real world data, which are collected in the

80
00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:08.140
course of routine practice, and when I say real world data, I'm

81
00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:12.020
generally rolling up all sources collected outside of the

82
00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:15.640
context of a randomized trial. So that would incorporate electronic health

83
00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:19.560
records, administrative claims data, disease registries,

84
00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:23.760
and potentially even more diffuse

85
00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.719
data types like social media data or wearable devices.

86
00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:31.520
So all of these secondary data sources potentially give us

87
00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:35.550
access to a lot of opportunities and a lot of benefits,

88
00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:39.830
including lower cost than large randomized trials, larger

89
00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:43.910
sample sizes, and rapid data availability and

90
00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:44.680
access.

91
00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:49.219
But I think one of the most exciting opportunities of doing

92
00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:53.120
research with real world data is the opportunity to access representative

93
00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:57.080
patient populations receiving care in the real world.

94
00:05:57.180 --> 00:06:00.620
So we're able to get a window into health and healthcare and treatment

95
00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:04.580
effectiveness in the context of routine clinical practice, rather

96
00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:08.590
than in the more verified and artificial environment of a randomized

97
00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:12.490
control trial.You can imagine that all of

98
00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.970
those benefits seem very appealing and are

99
00:06:16.230 --> 00:06:20.130
spurring the current enormous research interest in using

100
00:06:20.170 --> 00:06:22.550
these data sources for research purposes.

101
00:06:23.030 --> 00:06:26.690
But there's an important caveat, which is that real-world data

102
00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:30.410
differ in fundamental respects compared to randomized control trial

103
00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:34.270
data. So if we're going to incorporate these data into our analyses, we need to

104
00:06:34.310 --> 00:06:37.109
think carefully about the methods that we're going to use.

105
00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:43.150
I tend to think of trials and real-world data as having complementary

106
00:06:43.210 --> 00:06:47.080
strengths and weaknesses, and therefore, we would like to use them in ways that

107
00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:50.939
are complementary. So on this slide, on the left, I have trials, on the

108
00:06:50.990 --> 00:06:54.470
right, I have real-world data. And in the bold red, I've

109
00:06:54.530 --> 00:06:58.220
indicated the strengths of each, and in black, I'm indicating the

110
00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:01.430
weaknesses. And I've tried to line them up so that you can see that they somewhat

111
00:07:01.690 --> 00:07:05.430
complement each other. Trials give us access to high-quality

112
00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:09.520
data, very precise data collection standards, but are slow and

113
00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:11.850
expensive and not necessarily generalizable.

114
00:07:13.210 --> 00:07:16.850
Conversely, real-world data give us access to a broad representative

115
00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:20.730
patient population. They can be assembled relatively quickly and

116
00:07:20.810 --> 00:07:24.290
relatively cheaply, and the word "relatively" is doing a lot of work in that

117
00:07:24.330 --> 00:07:27.770
sentence, because these are difficult to curate,

118
00:07:28.390 --> 00:07:32.090
although not at the level of conducting a randomized control trial.

119
00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:35.670
But data quality is inconsistent.

120
00:07:36.770 --> 00:07:40.210
Data collection standards are unspecified, so we just see

121
00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:44.250
patients according to their own interaction with the healthcare system, which is

122
00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:47.780
not necessarily consistent across patients, providers, or

123
00:07:47.870 --> 00:07:48.470
systems.

124
00:07:50.050 --> 00:07:53.830
So what we'd like to do is use these two sources in a way that benefits from the

125
00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:57.310
strengths of each without degrading the quality of evidence

126
00:07:57.470 --> 00:08:01.410
associated with either. This is an example of two studies that were

127
00:08:01.450 --> 00:08:05.410
conducted answering similar questions, one in a real-world

128
00:08:05.470 --> 00:08:09.310
data population, which is the result on the left, and one in a phase three

129
00:08:09.370 --> 00:08:11.470
clinical trial, which is the result on the right.

130
00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:14.130
So the study that I'm showing here on the left

131
00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:19.010
was an observational study using oncology EHR data from Flatiron

132
00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:22.850
Health to do a head-to-head comparison of two treatments for advanced bladder

133
00:08:22.950 --> 00:08:23.430
cancer.

134
00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:28.230
We conducted that study because, at the time, there was no

135
00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.370
head-to-head comparison of these two treatments.

136
00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:33.890
Immunotherapy for advanced bladder cancer had been approved on the basis of a

137
00:08:33.990 --> 00:08:34.929
single-arm trial.

138
00:08:35.951 --> 00:08:39.750
So we were able to obtain the results on the left while the phase

139
00:08:39.810 --> 00:08:43.530
three trial, asking the same question in a similar patient population,

140
00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:47.730
was being conducted. And about six months later, the result on the right,

141
00:08:47.970 --> 00:08:49.970
which is from the phase three trial, was published.

142
00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:54.170
You can see qualitatively the conclusions are similar between these

143
00:08:54.190 --> 00:08:58.110
two, and I would say this is a good example of how the two data sources can be

144
00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:01.770
used in complementary ways. Real-world data gave us an answer more

145
00:09:01.830 --> 00:09:05.679
quickly that could fill an evidentiary gap while the randomized

146
00:09:05.710 --> 00:09:09.130
control trial was ongoing. But because of the higher risk of

147
00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:12.830
bias and the limitations of data quality in real-world data,

148
00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:17.090
we still need the randomized trial results to ultimately confirm

149
00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:19.610
and augment what we'd found in real-world data.

150
00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:25.530
So what are these data quality limitations that I'm alluding to?

151
00:09:26.050 --> 00:09:29.790
There are three different types of discrepancies that

152
00:09:29.810 --> 00:09:33.750
arise between real-world data and randomized controlled trials that could

153
00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:36.230
potentially introduce bias into our analyses.

154
00:09:36.730 --> 00:09:40.450
And on this slide, I've grouped them into three components, differences in the

155
00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:44.290
patients, differences in the care environment, and differences in the

156
00:09:44.350 --> 00:09:45.150
data quality.

157
00:09:46.610 --> 00:09:50.490
Differences in the patient population between patients participating in a trial

158
00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:54.150
and patients captured in a real-world data source, I would describe as

159
00:09:54.190 --> 00:09:56.250
representing a source of selection bias.

160
00:09:56.550 --> 00:10:00.510
So the patients who either have had the opportunity or have chosen to participate

161
00:10:00.530 --> 00:10:04.290
in a trial are not necessarily the same as patients in the

162
00:10:04.330 --> 00:10:07.280
broader patient population being treated in the real world.

163
00:10:08.210 --> 00:10:11.850
Additionally, typically, oncology clinical trials have a lengthy list of

164
00:10:11.890 --> 00:10:15.570
eligibility criteria, and many of those eligibility criteria are

165
00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:19.510
measured inconsistently or incompletely in real-world data sources.

166
00:10:19.890 --> 00:10:23.630
So although we'd like to look at the same patient population meeting the same

167
00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:27.600
eligibility criteria in the real world and in a randomized trial, we're

168
00:10:27.670 --> 00:10:30.910
often unable to do so because of the limitations of the data source.

169
00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:37.110
The supportive care environment in the real world also potentially

170
00:10:37.150 --> 00:10:40.930
differs from that in the trial environment, and that could represent

171
00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:44.790
aspects of treatment delivery or supportive care as well as

172
00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:48.810
monitoring. So if monitoring of patients, if follow-up

173
00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:52.630
is different between the trial environment and real-world environment,

174
00:10:53.010 --> 00:10:56.770
then potentially outcome ascertainment is also going to look different between the

175
00:10:56.810 --> 00:11:00.630
two data sources, and this could also lead to the appearance of

176
00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:04.170
treatment heterogeneity between the two data sources.

177
00:11:05.430 --> 00:11:07.490
And then finally, the data themselves.

178
00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:11.570
If you think of data sources like electronic health records or administrative

179
00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:15.550
claims data, the data themselves are much more

180
00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:18.930
heterogeneous, are inconsistently collected, have

181
00:11:19.250 --> 00:11:22.910
unprespecified methods for outcome ascertainment, are

182
00:11:23.030 --> 00:11:26.570
missing many of the data elements that we're interested in, and in many cases,

183
00:11:26.670 --> 00:11:30.330
we're going to be deriving the data elements that we want to use from structured

184
00:11:30.350 --> 00:11:34.170
fields such as ICD codes or procedure codes, which

185
00:11:34.290 --> 00:11:37.420
have heterogeneous coding conventions across clinical

186
00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:41.750
systems, across clinicians. And those differences in things like

187
00:11:41.790 --> 00:11:45.610
coding conventions could create spurious appearance of differences

188
00:11:45.670 --> 00:11:49.310
between treatments in the trial environment versus the

189
00:11:49.350 --> 00:11:51.410
real-world environment.

190
00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:57.760
So one opportunity for incorporating data from the real

191
00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:01.430
world into a clinical trial is by augmenting the

192
00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:05.070
control arm of a trial with patients from a real-world data

193
00:12:05.130 --> 00:12:07.450
source who are receiving the same treatment.

194
00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:12.150
There are two different ways that we could consider doing that.One is

195
00:12:12.210 --> 00:12:13.950
via an externally controlled trial.

196
00:12:14.590 --> 00:12:18.310
So in an externally controlled trial, we would have a single-arm

197
00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:21.850
trial in which patients solely receive the experimental treatment,

198
00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:25.950
and then we're going to compare those patients to those receiving a standard of

199
00:12:26.030 --> 00:12:27.570
care treatment in the real world.

200
00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:32.750
That approach has a high risk of bias because all of the differences between

201
00:12:32.770 --> 00:12:36.370
real-world data sources and trials that I just described on the previous

202
00:12:36.410 --> 00:12:36.850
slide

203
00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:41.610
will erroneously or spuriously look like differences between

204
00:12:41.630 --> 00:12:43.729
the experimental treatment and the standard of care.

205
00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:47.670
In other words, all of those differences that are attributable to the data source

206
00:12:48.010 --> 00:12:51.850
and the environment will be 100% confounded with the

207
00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:53.590
comparison of the two treatment arms.

208
00:12:55.390 --> 00:12:58.470
Another opportunity is the hybrid control trial design.

209
00:12:58.830 --> 00:13:02.390
So in the hybrid control trial design, we'll take a randomized trial in which

210
00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:05.630
patients are randomized to the experimental treatment as well as the standard of

211
00:13:05.730 --> 00:13:06.030
care,

212
00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:10.790
and then we're going to augment that internal control arm with an additional

213
00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:14.150
external control arm drawn solely from real-world data.

214
00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:18.890
So in this trial design, we have patients receiving the standard of care

215
00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:22.530
treatment, both in the context of the trial and in the real world.

216
00:13:23.330 --> 00:13:27.090
That allows us to distinguish between differences between the two treatments

217
00:13:27.290 --> 00:13:30.530
and differences between the care environments and the data quality.

218
00:13:30.970 --> 00:13:34.790
So the hybrid control trial design, while also potentially suffering from

219
00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:38.400
bias by introducing differences between real-world data and

220
00:13:38.470 --> 00:13:39.540
randomized trial data,

221
00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:44.510
is able to accommodate those differences by leveraging information

222
00:13:44.750 --> 00:13:48.320
comparing those two treatment arms, the control-treated patients in the

223
00:13:48.390 --> 00:13:51.390
trial and the control-treated patients in the real world.

224
00:13:54.130 --> 00:13:57.570
The reason that we might be interested in conducting a hybrid control trial despite

225
00:13:57.630 --> 00:14:01.510
the potential limitations and the potential introduction of bias, is that

226
00:14:01.550 --> 00:14:04.850
it may decrease the overall size of the randomized trial

227
00:14:05.010 --> 00:14:08.750
portion of the study, so we may be able to complete the trial more

228
00:14:08.810 --> 00:14:10.050
quickly and more cheaply.

229
00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:14.670
We could potentially also accelerate enrollment because it allows us to vary the

230
00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:17.910
randomization ratio towards the experimental arm.

231
00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:21.740
So rather than randomizing patients one to one, we could randomize a higher

232
00:14:21.740 --> 00:14:25.690
proportion of patients into the experimental arm, which may be more appealing both

233
00:14:25.730 --> 00:14:29.210
to patients and clinicians and may accelerate enrollment into the

234
00:14:29.250 --> 00:14:33.230
trial. However, all of the differences between the data sources

235
00:14:33.250 --> 00:14:37.030
and the patient populations that I mentioned are potentially going to bias our

236
00:14:37.050 --> 00:14:40.740
comparisons and need to be carefully addressed via our analysis and

237
00:14:40.810 --> 00:14:41.210
design.

238
00:14:44.190 --> 00:14:47.740
So at a high level, there are four different ways that we could think about

239
00:14:47.810 --> 00:14:49.610
analyzing a hybrid control trial.

240
00:14:50.290 --> 00:14:53.950
In the slides that I have coming up next, I'm illustrating

241
00:14:54.090 --> 00:14:57.830
the randomized trial portion of the study by the two

242
00:14:57.950 --> 00:14:58.970
circles on the right,

243
00:14:59.910 --> 00:15:02.030
the internal control arm and the intervention arm.

244
00:15:02.110 --> 00:15:05.610
So patients are randomized to those two arms, and they have the intervention arm

245
00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:08.730
larger to represent that we're able to randomize more patients into the

246
00:15:08.750 --> 00:15:12.240
intervention arm. The color of the patients inside the circles

247
00:15:12.630 --> 00:15:16.280
represents the distribution of patient characteristics, and since the patients in

248
00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:20.130
the randomized trial were randomly assigned to the control arm or the

249
00:15:20.150 --> 00:15:23.890
intervention arm, the distribution of the colors of the figures in those two

250
00:15:23.930 --> 00:15:25.070
circles should be the same.

251
00:15:26.290 --> 00:15:29.850
In contrast, the real-world data control arm in green on the left

252
00:15:30.070 --> 00:15:33.810
represents additional patients that we're going to use to augment the control arm

253
00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:37.690
who come from the real world. And consequently, the distribution of patient

254
00:15:37.770 --> 00:15:41.130
characteristics in that arm is not necessarily the same.

255
00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:45.880
So to be very conservative, we could analyze only the patients from the randomized

256
00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:49.830
portion of the trial, which we believe would control bias but would

257
00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:50.690
be inefficient.

258
00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:56.550
Conversely, we could fully incorporate information from the real-world control

259
00:15:56.670 --> 00:15:59.090
arm, which I'm going to refer to as full pooling.

260
00:15:59.870 --> 00:16:03.450
And under full pooling, we've now potentially introduced bias into our

261
00:16:03.550 --> 00:16:07.410
study due to incorporating these patients who have different characteristics into

262
00:16:07.430 --> 00:16:10.710
our control arm, but it's maximally efficient in that it

263
00:16:10.810 --> 00:16:13.000
maximally uses the available information.

264
00:16:15.110 --> 00:16:19.020
To try to account for that potential bias, there are a number of approaches that

265
00:16:19.030 --> 00:16:22.310
are collectively referred to as static or dynamic borrowing.

266
00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:26.750
And in these approaches, we're going to up or down-weight the information from that

267
00:16:26.810 --> 00:16:30.610
real-world data control arm according to the similarity between the

268
00:16:30.650 --> 00:16:32.949
real-world patients and the trial patients.

269
00:16:33.329 --> 00:16:36.970
So in this example, the real-world patients are somewhat different from the trial

270
00:16:37.050 --> 00:16:40.870
patients, and so that entire circle has been down-weighted to reflect

271
00:16:40.890 --> 00:16:44.430
the fact that the evidence coming from that information is not quite

272
00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:46.710
comparable to the trial information.

273
00:16:49.390 --> 00:16:52.710
And then finally, we could take a propensity score-based weighting approach in

274
00:16:52.810 --> 00:16:56.290
which rather than up or down-weighting the entire real-world data data

275
00:16:56.390 --> 00:17:00.310
source, we're going to up or down-weight individual patients within

276
00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:04.250
the real-world data control arm proportional to their similarity

277
00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:08.171
to patients inside the trial. So patients in the real-world data control

278
00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:11.891
arm who have characteristics that are underrepresented relative

279
00:17:11.899 --> 00:17:15.230
to what that patient subgroup looks like in the trial would be

280
00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:18.570
up-weighted. Those who are overrepresented would be down-weighted.

281
00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:25.230
I'm going to show you the relative performance of these different approaches in a

282
00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:29.150
few simulation studies in which I'm going to vary the strength of the true

283
00:17:29.230 --> 00:17:32.790
treatment effect. I'm going to show you results for a randomization

284
00:17:32.870 --> 00:17:36.790
ratio of two to one, and then I'm going to vary the strength of confounding,

285
00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:40.770
by which I mean the systematic difference between patients in the real

286
00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:44.290
world and patients in the trial, between what I'm going to refer to as mild

287
00:17:44.350 --> 00:17:45.930
confounding and strong confounding.

288
00:17:46.890 --> 00:17:50.130
And I'll show you results for bias, type one error, and power.

289
00:17:52.610 --> 00:17:56.390
So these are results as we vary the hazard ratio, the true treatment effect

290
00:17:56.490 --> 00:18:00.370
across the x-axis from about 0.5 up to one

291
00:18:00.410 --> 00:18:02.170
for each of the methods that I've discussed.

292
00:18:02.570 --> 00:18:05.210
So in green, I have bias results for the trial.

293
00:18:05.310 --> 00:18:09.270
We expect that the trial is unbiased, it's protected by randomization, and you see

294
00:18:09.350 --> 00:18:13.090
that's what this slide illustrates.If we fully pull

295
00:18:13.190 --> 00:18:16.790
in all of the information from the real-world data, that's

296
00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:20.570
represented by the red line, and it has very substantial bias.

297
00:18:21.270 --> 00:18:25.130
We can reduce that bias by using a static borrowing approach,

298
00:18:25.430 --> 00:18:28.750
which downweights the evidence from the real-world data source.

299
00:18:29.110 --> 00:18:32.890
But you can see all of the blue lines here also demonstrate

300
00:18:32.930 --> 00:18:36.850
significant bias due to that systematic confounding, that systematic difference

301
00:18:36.870 --> 00:18:39.150
between real-world and trial patients.

302
00:18:40.070 --> 00:18:43.270
And then finally, if we take a propensity score-based approach, we're able to

303
00:18:43.330 --> 00:18:46.839
eliminate that bias. But an important caveat here is,

304
00:18:47.170 --> 00:18:50.750
although the propensity score is appropriately adjusting for systematic

305
00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:54.630
differences, it relies on the assumption that we have access to all of the

306
00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:58.659
covariates, all of the confounders that we need to adjust for in order

307
00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:00.590
to be able to explain those differences.

308
00:19:03.250 --> 00:19:07.070
Type one error follows very similarly to what you would expect based on those bias

309
00:19:07.130 --> 00:19:11.050
results. The trial controls type one error because of the systematic

310
00:19:11.090 --> 00:19:14.110
bias in full pooling and all of the static borrowing approaches.

311
00:19:14.390 --> 00:19:18.310
They have enormously inflated type one error in this example, and the

312
00:19:18.330 --> 00:19:22.270
propensity score weighting approach is able to return type one

313
00:19:22.330 --> 00:19:24.130
error to approximately the nominal level.

314
00:19:26.730 --> 00:19:30.630
And then finally, if we look at power, you can see that we apparently get a

315
00:19:30.670 --> 00:19:34.480
power boost from full pooling or the static borrowing approaches.

316
00:19:35.270 --> 00:19:38.700
But we know that those approaches lead to inflated type one error.

317
00:19:38.810 --> 00:19:42.590
So we wouldn't want to trust these power results essentially because we know that

318
00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:46.430
this increase in power is due to the bias in those approaches.

319
00:19:47.110 --> 00:19:50.690
The propensity score-based approach, which was approximately able to control type

320
00:19:50.730 --> 00:19:53.110
one error, still gives us a power boost.

321
00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:56.850
So we are getting some benefit from incorporating the real-world patients,

322
00:19:57.750 --> 00:20:00.450
without inflating type one error or introducing bias.

323
00:20:03.070 --> 00:20:06.570
I'll wrap up just by showing you what this looks like in a real-world example.

324
00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:10.470
So in this study, I used data from a real trial

325
00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:14.010
comparing two different treatments for prostate cancer, in which patients were

326
00:20:14.090 --> 00:20:17.870
randomized to the experimental arm or the standard of care at a two to one

327
00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:18.470
ratio.

328
00:20:19.590 --> 00:20:23.530
I then created a pseudo real-world data arm in which I resampled

329
00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:27.480
patients from the control arm of the trial, but I did it according to sampling

330
00:20:27.550 --> 00:20:31.370
probabilities that systematically distorted the relationship

331
00:20:31.390 --> 00:20:35.170
between patient covariates and whether or not a patient was seen in the

332
00:20:35.190 --> 00:20:38.490
trial environment or the pseudo real-world data environment.

333
00:20:40.770 --> 00:20:44.730
What I mean by that is shown here. So here I'm summarizing a few of the patient

334
00:20:44.770 --> 00:20:46.659
characteristics for the patients in this trial.

335
00:20:47.390 --> 00:20:51.200
You can see with the control arm and the intervention arm, which were randomized,

336
00:20:51.430 --> 00:20:54.310
all of the patient characteristics are distributed similarly.

337
00:20:55.170 --> 00:20:58.990
In the pseudo real-world data arm, because I have sampled the patients according

338
00:20:59.130 --> 00:21:02.570
to ECOG performance status and according to PSA, I've

339
00:21:02.590 --> 00:21:06.410
systematically distorted this distribution relative to the way that it

340
00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:07.550
looks in the trial.

341
00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:13.750
The implication is that if we compare survival in those three sources,

342
00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:17.790
the pseudo EHR or pseudo real-world data arm has much poorer

343
00:21:17.830 --> 00:21:20.710
survival compared to either of the two arms in the trial.

344
00:21:21.190 --> 00:21:25.050
So you can imagine if I just naively pool the yellow patients in with the blue

345
00:21:25.110 --> 00:21:29.030
patients, there's going to be a massively inflated

346
00:21:29.130 --> 00:21:32.450
apparent treatment effect. Patients treated with the standard of care are going to

347
00:21:32.490 --> 00:21:36.070
look like they do much more poorly than patients receiving the experimental

348
00:21:36.110 --> 00:21:37.810
treatment in the context of the trial.

349
00:21:41.550 --> 00:21:44.950
Here are point estimates and confidence intervals for each of the methods that I'm

350
00:21:44.970 --> 00:21:48.690
describing, and I'm comparing them to the black vertical bar, which

351
00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:52.750
is the point estimate from the trial, and then the gray bar around

352
00:21:52.790 --> 00:21:55.250
it is the confidence interval from the trial.

353
00:21:56.310 --> 00:22:00.100
Similar to the simulation results, you can see that full pooling and the static

354
00:22:00.170 --> 00:22:02.110
borrowing approaches are enormously biased.

355
00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:05.270
They give us an estimate very far away from the trial estimate.

356
00:22:06.110 --> 00:22:10.050
Dynamic borrowing, which dynamically determines how much information we

357
00:22:10.070 --> 00:22:13.610
want to incorporate from the real world, depending on similarity between the

358
00:22:13.650 --> 00:22:17.350
patient populations, gets us back to something very close to the trial,

359
00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:20.450
but also barely increases efficiency.

360
00:22:20.490 --> 00:22:24.430
So the width of the confidence interval in the dynamic borrowing setting is

361
00:22:24.510 --> 00:22:27.890
almost exactly the same as the width of the trial-only estimate.

362
00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:32.960
Both of the propensity score-based approaches get us closer to

363
00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:36.920
the trial-only estimate, and in particular, the propensity score-based weighting,

364
00:22:37.030 --> 00:22:40.980
which is more flexible than a stratification approach, gets us very close to the

365
00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:42.910
trial and has reduced

366
00:22:43.990 --> 00:22:46.410
the width of the confidence interval by quite a bit.

367
00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:52.670
So in conclusion, there are a lot of opportunities for using

368
00:22:52.690 --> 00:22:55.830
real-world data to address some of the limitations of clinical trials,

369
00:22:56.190 --> 00:22:59.710
including their speed, their cost, and their limited

370
00:22:59.790 --> 00:23:03.690
generalizability. But there are many methodological challenges that we have to

371
00:23:03.710 --> 00:23:07.390
think about carefully, particularly related to data quality.

372
00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:11.130
So we really need to reflect carefully on those three sources of discrepancy

373
00:23:11.170 --> 00:23:14.830
between real-world data and trials that I mentioned earlier and think

374
00:23:14.930 --> 00:23:18.750
about the approaches that we're going to use to address things like missing data,

375
00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:21.650
measurement error, and differential outcome ascertainment.

376
00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:26.390
There are also systematic differences between trial and real-world patient

377
00:23:26.430 --> 00:23:30.410
populations and care environments that we have to be careful to use

378
00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:34.270
methods that will allow us to disentangle differences between

379
00:23:34.350 --> 00:23:38.300
those care environments and patient populations and differences in treatments

380
00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:42.130
that we want to compare. I think there are a lot of opportunities

381
00:23:42.190 --> 00:23:45.620
for addressing these challenges via methodological innovation.

382
00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:49.550
I think that advances in AI, especially LLMs, do

383
00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:52.990
hold the potential to unlock additional confounder information from the

384
00:23:53.010 --> 00:23:56.710
EHR, which would allow us to use these real-world data more

385
00:23:56.730 --> 00:24:00.010
effectively. But we have to do so in a way that preserves

386
00:24:00.050 --> 00:24:03.990
transparency and preserves research rigor, so we don't degrade the quality of

387
00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:06.770
the evidence as we bring in additional real-world data.

388
00:24:07.850 --> 00:24:08.170
Thank you.

389
00:24:16.046 --> 00:24:17.406
Thanks, Rebecca. Great start.

390
00:24:18.466 --> 00:24:19.986
And for those who came in

391
00:24:21.226 --> 00:24:25.046
a little bit late, we are going to give all three talks

392
00:24:25.586 --> 00:24:29.166
and then have a panel discussion at the

393
00:24:29.266 --> 00:24:33.186
end to address

394
00:24:33.246 --> 00:24:34.266
topics that come up.

395
00:24:35.126 --> 00:24:37.466
The next speaker is Dr. Neil Meropol,

396
00:24:38.486 --> 00:24:41.946
who is Senior Advisor to Flatiron Health,

397
00:24:42.446 --> 00:24:46.286
and he is the Principal Investigator Elect of the

398
00:24:46.506 --> 00:24:48.066
ASCO TAPER study.

399
00:24:49.146 --> 00:24:49.366
Neil.

400
00:24:51.906 --> 00:24:52.906
Thanks, Peter.

401
00:25:00.926 --> 00:25:02.526
Okay, well, I'm going to provide

402
00:25:03.486 --> 00:25:04.786
a complementary

403
00:25:05.706 --> 00:25:09.486
perspective on the use of real-world data in clinical trial design and

404
00:25:09.526 --> 00:25:13.126
execution, coming from the perspective of

405
00:25:13.266 --> 00:25:17.246
an oncologist who's been a clinical investigator and

406
00:25:17.306 --> 00:25:20.666
a health outcomes researcher working with real-world data, in

407
00:25:20.705 --> 00:25:21.326
particular,

408
00:25:22.186 --> 00:25:25.186
data derived from electronic health records.

409
00:25:25.286 --> 00:25:28.326
So my talk is going to be divided into

410
00:25:29.206 --> 00:25:33.106
two broad sections. The first, I'm going to talk about how we go

411
00:25:33.206 --> 00:25:37.186
about curating, extracting research-ready data

412
00:25:37.606 --> 00:25:41.466
from electronic health records, and then move on from there to

413
00:25:41.706 --> 00:25:44.966
how that curation approach can be

414
00:25:45.006 --> 00:25:48.166
applied to supporting clinical trials.

415
00:25:51.026 --> 00:25:54.126
To amplify on what Rebecca

416
00:25:54.986 --> 00:25:58.466
discussed previously, there are a variety of forms

417
00:25:58.706 --> 00:26:02.546
of real-world data, data relating to patient health

418
00:26:02.626 --> 00:26:04.786
status, routinely collected

419
00:26:06.486 --> 00:26:10.126
in a variety of ways. And my focus is going to be on electronic health

420
00:26:10.206 --> 00:26:14.166
records, but for completeness, I'm highlighting some of the other

421
00:26:14.226 --> 00:26:15.026
sources here.

422
00:26:17.386 --> 00:26:21.026
Why are people interested in EHRs as a

423
00:26:21.086 --> 00:26:24.706
data resource for clinical research?

424
00:26:25.665 --> 00:26:27.306
Rich source of patient-level data.

425
00:26:28.286 --> 00:26:31.386
It integrates multiple data sources, radiology,

426
00:26:31.586 --> 00:26:34.886
genomics, laboratory, clinical, pathologic.

427
00:26:35.666 --> 00:26:39.186
The documentation happens in real time, so you can actually get a

428
00:26:39.286 --> 00:26:43.186
very current picture of a patient

429
00:26:43.306 --> 00:26:45.226
journey through the electronic health record.

430
00:26:45.866 --> 00:26:49.856
The information's digitized, so it's ready to be curated,

431
00:26:49.946 --> 00:26:53.026
to be analyzed in its native form.

432
00:26:54.126 --> 00:26:57.586
Because it's part of the routine clinical care

433
00:26:58.366 --> 00:27:01.986
workflow, EHR data as a real-world data source

434
00:27:02.486 --> 00:27:06.386
is really great for understanding how care is delivered.

435
00:27:07.186 --> 00:27:11.166
And finally, in terms of representativeness, it's well known

436
00:27:11.486 --> 00:27:15.306
that the patients who take part in traditional clinical trials tend

437
00:27:15.386 --> 00:27:18.866
to not be representative of the overall patient population.

438
00:27:19.626 --> 00:27:22.886
Real-world data, on the other hand, has the potential to be fully

439
00:27:22.986 --> 00:27:23.746
representative.

440
00:27:25.866 --> 00:27:29.446
So when I think about the types of data that could be

441
00:27:29.486 --> 00:27:33.046
obtained in the electronic health record, and this relates to how we

442
00:27:33.126 --> 00:27:36.726
curate those data, there are three broad types of data.

443
00:27:37.146 --> 00:27:40.246
One are the structured data that is entered as numbers,

444
00:27:40.646 --> 00:27:44.006
drop-down fields, laboratory values, and so forth.

445
00:27:44.506 --> 00:27:46.806
There's unstructured EHR data that

446
00:27:47.626 --> 00:27:50.046
finds its way in through physician narratives

447
00:27:50.886 --> 00:27:53.426
and reports of radiology and so forth.

448
00:27:54.606 --> 00:27:56.346
And then there are external data sources,

449
00:27:57.206 --> 00:27:57.826
like

450
00:27:58.746 --> 00:28:02.226
genomic data that are performed in a

451
00:28:02.306 --> 00:28:06.046
third-party laboratory. They might be sent in as

452
00:28:06.106 --> 00:28:09.486
PDFs and integrated into the EHR.

453
00:28:10.286 --> 00:28:13.986
There are claims data that are not typically part of the EHR.

454
00:28:14.006 --> 00:28:17.666
There's mortality data from obituaries that are used to

455
00:28:18.126 --> 00:28:22.036
supplement mortality variables when EHRs are used for

456
00:28:22.106 --> 00:28:24.946
research that come from external sources.

457
00:28:25.276 --> 00:28:29.246
And through tokenization and other methods, these can be linked with

458
00:28:29.366 --> 00:28:30.586
EHR data.

459
00:28:32.006 --> 00:28:35.346
Now, in terms of the unstructured EHR data, this is the biggest nut to crack,

460
00:28:36.106 --> 00:28:39.926
because it requires interpretation of data

461
00:28:39.946 --> 00:28:41.726
that are not research-ready.

462
00:28:42.866 --> 00:28:46.186
And there are three broad categories, and this is a very

463
00:28:46.226 --> 00:28:49.826
rapidly evolving field. There are three ways that these data are

464
00:28:49.886 --> 00:28:53.346
typically curated today. One, shown on the bottom, is human

465
00:28:53.366 --> 00:28:56.946
abstraction. This has been historically the gold standard.

466
00:28:57.986 --> 00:29:01.326
A person reading a chart and turning a

467
00:29:01.406 --> 00:29:04.626
sentence into a data element ready for analysis.

468
00:29:06.006 --> 00:29:06.366
There are

469
00:29:07.386 --> 00:29:11.286
machine learning approaches that are applied to

470
00:29:12.226 --> 00:29:15.286
basically natural language process

471
00:29:16.426 --> 00:29:19.846
reading of charts, and the machine learning

472
00:29:19.946 --> 00:29:23.226
algorithms are trained and

473
00:29:23.286 --> 00:29:24.746
tested against

474
00:29:25.766 --> 00:29:29.226
a gold standard data set that has been human

475
00:29:29.286 --> 00:29:33.126
curated. And then more recently, the application of large language

476
00:29:33.246 --> 00:29:36.646
models. So being able to prompt the machine with

477
00:29:37.986 --> 00:29:41.956
routine conversational language to give instructions

478
00:29:42.246 --> 00:29:45.806
for what the machine should do in terms of reading the chart and pulling out

479
00:29:46.006 --> 00:29:49.646
information, again, requiring validation of the approach.

480
00:29:50.566 --> 00:29:52.866
So how do we

481
00:29:53.926 --> 00:29:57.726
assess the quality of real-world data obtained from EHRs?

482
00:29:57.966 --> 00:30:01.826
This is absolutely critical for minimizing bias as

483
00:30:01.886 --> 00:30:05.736
much as you can related to the data that are

484
00:30:05.786 --> 00:30:08.186
obtained. So there's questions of reliability.

485
00:30:08.206 --> 00:30:11.236
Is that data element actually what was

486
00:30:11.986 --> 00:30:15.786
documented in the chart? Do two methods of

487
00:30:15.846 --> 00:30:19.546
interpretation or two interpreters over time come up with the

488
00:30:19.626 --> 00:30:23.278
same data point?For that

489
00:30:23.298 --> 00:30:24.398
particular parameter.

490
00:30:25.258 --> 00:30:29.218
How relevant is the data in the EHR to the research

491
00:30:29.318 --> 00:30:32.778
question? You'll hear a lot about fitness for purpose, and that's absolutely

492
00:30:32.878 --> 00:30:36.658
critical in understanding whether a real-world data source is

493
00:30:36.698 --> 00:30:40.518
appropriate to be integrated with clinical trial data.

494
