1449
01:25:41.684 --> 01:25:45.264
So in the missing data literature, and this is getting kind of methods

1450
01:25:45.444 --> 01:25:48.904
nerdy, but in the missing data literature, there are three general

1451
01:25:49.404 --> 01:25:52.874
missing data mechanisms: missing completely at random, missing at random, and

1452
01:25:52.904 --> 01:25:56.844
missing not at random. And so missing completely at random leads

1453
01:25:56.884 --> 01:25:56.944
to

1454
01:25:58.004 --> 01:26:00.464
no bias, pretty much under any analysis you might propose.

1455
01:26:01.064 --> 01:26:04.364
And that's when there's absolutely nothing systematic about the missingness.

1456
01:26:04.404 --> 01:26:08.164
It's completely random. It's like somebody just lost those records, and it's

1457
01:26:08.204 --> 01:26:08.984
nothing to do with anything else.

1458
01:26:09.804 --> 01:26:13.584
Missing at random is systematic missingness that's predictable based on the

1459
01:26:13.604 --> 01:26:17.184
data. So in some of the cases that you're talking about, like

1460
01:26:18.964 --> 01:26:22.064
clinicians in academic settings are less likely to record stage, that's a

1461
01:26:22.124 --> 01:26:25.504
systematic missingness, but it's a predictable systematic missingness because it's

1462
01:26:25.564 --> 01:26:29.544
missingness that's due to academic versus community site.

1463
01:26:29.884 --> 01:26:33.204
So if you have that kind of predictable missingness, that's actually not a big

1464
01:26:33.244 --> 01:26:36.784
concern. Imputation can handle that kind of setting.

1465
01:26:37.184 --> 01:26:41.124
So missing not at random is the really problematic one, where the value

1466
01:26:41.164 --> 01:26:44.804
of the variable itself is what determines whether or not it's likely to be missing.

1467
01:26:46.044 --> 01:26:49.984
I've seen methods in the literature, especially in the machine learning

1468
01:26:50.024 --> 01:26:53.914
